segments.text: Did you have an opportunity when you were head of the department to do any research, or did a member of your department do any research, or did that change over the years?
Well, I always felt that we needed research in the department.
Of course, it was in the agricultural experiment station that Dr. Schmetter had charged.
He had several men with him.
In fact, Dr. Turk got started with him.
And we were loaded with teaching hours and with responsibilities, more or less extension work of answering letters.
And anything on poisonous plants, I got it.
And it made me up poisonous plants from West Texas that I had never seen.
And I'd send it back to
a man who was at Sonora Experimental Station, a botanist, Mr. Corey, V.L.
Corey.
And he would classify and send back to me, the name back to me.
But I got an enormous number of plants to classify.
They thought, well, by George, they just sent a leaf.
And I'd write back, and I'd tell them I needed a bloom or something like that.
But we did lots of that.
I really got into trouble.
by having taken that course with Dr. Pommel.
But I learned something.
I learned appreciation of plants with Dr. Pommel.
When I'd notice a livestock, he'd just grunt.
No approval or disapproval, but he'd see a plant at the same time.
And he says, go over there and get that plant, will you?
And I'd have to crawl through the wire.
and get that plant and take it over to him, and he'd tell me what that plant was.
But any time I'd open my mouth about livestock, he'd see a plant.
And so he got me botanically minded.
I got to appreciating plants, and I realized to get along with him more peacefully, why I would need to look at those plants.
But in general, did you have or did any of your staff members in the department have much time for research?
Did that change over the years?
I guess all of us did a little pilot work of this and that would get interested.
I got interested in allergic reactions of animals and it was all from Physiology or Pharmacology.
And I remember having presented a paper at the AVMA in Chicago on allergic reactions in dogs.
I happened to know Dr. Black, who was in Brown and moved to Dallas, and he became an allergist up there, and I went by to see him when I was up there in 34.
And he encouraged me.
So it was before 34, because I had presented that paper in 33.
But I got in contact with him, and he demonstrated.
I think we went up there, and Mrs. Burns had a brother in Dallas.
It was a telephone company.
We went up there, and I went by to see Dr. Black.
And he demonstrated what a positive reaction was and what a negative was.
So he got me started on the allergy testing.
get testing some dogs.
But that was research work of a sort.
And so all of us, I guess, have ever taught in the department of, perhaps, piddled with things.
I don't know whether reports in the literature have been made.
I recall that one that I made to the national meeting.
I know Eads got interested in research.
He was working on a degree, though, in measuring the alveolar air in animals.
He had to devise a certain instrument to put around the muzzle of the animal, so he'd have to breathe into this.
He did a very good piece of work on that.
He reported that in the journal, I think, probably in the first volume one, number one of our research journal.
I don't recall the year, probably in 38, something like that.
Did it appear in the School of Vet and Medicine that there was more emphasis placed on research over the years, or less, or did that change?
No, more, because then when research and extension became a part of the teaching, all in the same department, in colleges and schools.
schools because they didn't become colleges until 63, until the name was changed from a college to university.
Each department increased, of course, the amount of research work, and when that happenedand that happened in 48, when they consolidated
But I remember in the designing of the physiology department, the building where it exists now, we were on the third floor.
Dr. Bowden was dean, and he says, the president says, I hate to tell you this, but says, the president says, design this building with what you are in the present status.
And I said, I've been wanting to incorporate some research.
He says, no, you design it as of right now.
I said, you're not on research?
So I designed it for teaching.
And I remember contacting the architect.
I said, how much space?
on wall work and microscope space do you allow for students?"
He says, 30 inches.
So I prepared for a lab of 32 in each of those labs.
We could handle 64 students, both of them.
But then I started
Some of these Pakistanis, East Pakistanis came in on us, in addition to 64.
And they take 65, 66, and add them.
I said, that's not, I raised quite a lot of objection to it.
And I said, we prepared for 32.
All the departments could absorb them.
But I was too conservative in that planning.
I should have added some.
I might have gotten by with it.
Maybe the others did.
When did foreign students start coming to the vet school?
Oh, I don't know whether you'd call a Puerto Rican a foreign student, but we had one.
One member in Class of 1936 was from Puerto Rico.
That was before it was a state.
And that was the first one I recall.
Not from Mexico, because that was a national, but we had students from Mexico and South America in the ag course.
I've always had some Latinos in my classes.
But in veterinary medicine, of course when they made that agreement with Pakistan, East Pakistan,
microbiology, physiology, and parasitology.
We had quite a few graduate students, but we found quite a few of them inferior.
They had not taken sufficient, they didn't have enough math, didn't have enough chemistry.
And we had a little difficulty with them, and one or two of them failed.
Was this in the 30s?
I'd say in the 40s.
In the 40s?
After the Second World War?
Yes.
But I don't know how many Pakistanis there are now, but we used to have quite a few of them.
Occasionally we'd get one.
I got one that was very good.
He'd gotten two degrees, one from the University of London, and I'd forgotten where the other one was from, Cambridge or somewhere.
But he didn't mind getting his hands dirty.
Some of them have caste systems, see, and some of that work that we did was menial to them.
And they wanted to observe.
And they'd go from lab group to lab group, and just wanted to look over somebody's shoulder.
But we'd give them the materials, and we'd had a pretty hard time enforcing that each student must pitch in and do his work.
But we finally got pretty good cooperation.
But this, I've forgotten his, Ahmed, I don't recall now his full name.
But he had two degrees.
He took a master's with me.
And then he got his PhD in biochemistry.
So he had four foreign degrees and one from his home.
So he had five degrees.
But no one has heard anything from him.
When they cracked down and got any more intellectuals over there, they tried to weed them out and assassinate them.
I'm afraid he lost his life.
I don't know.
But he certainly was an intelligent person.
And with degrees, with all that many degrees.
He was the head of a department.
He went back and headed the department.
Oh, I remember having Shabani as a student.
He finished in agronomy.
His father was finance minister of Iran, and his father would send him a $10,000 check.
Dean Kyle would
of Agriculture would give him permission to go to Washington, some bank up there had deposited.
And he'd come back, and Dr. Pearson was head of nutrition, biochemistry and nutrition, and he says, you know, if we could keep, and he was the one that talked me into taking him.
You see, when he finished in 40,
Got a degree in agronomy in about 44, 45.
He couldn't get home.
Couldn't get to Iran from any direction.
And he stayed over and took a graduate degree.
Got him from agronomy.
He went to biochemistry.
And then after the war, after he finished those, he got his master's.
He still couldn't get home.
So he went up to Tennessee, up to Kentucky and worked for a distillery.
And...
Schenley Brothers, Schenley's I think.
Schenley and Schenley, I guess, whatever it's called.
And he was on nutrition, I think, from the standpoint of byproducts of distillation by the fiber content.
But Shabani, the last I heard of him was up in the high, in the
that are very responsible.
I don't know whether there's a state or in the national government, but I don't know now since you may be dead by now.
What about tenure?
In the form of student address unknown, so that's suspicious.
Yeah, what about tenure requirements?
Tell me about those.
That came back since I retired.
That's...
I know Didn't you have any tenure requirements back in the 20s?
None whatsoever when I knew them though.
Really?
They were talking about it.
I think I remember going and visiting the American Association of University Professors when that thing came up, and some of them, of course, were against it.
They said, we're firing all right, or we are.
They finally got it in, I don't know, perhaps even before Mr. Rutter came in.
I know it was effective when he was president.
Possibly something before, but it is of comparison to the recent origin.
I would say in the 50s or 60s, Mr. Rutter came in 60 or 61, I think.
It may have been with Mr. Gilchrist's time, but I don't know whether it's any different than what it was before or not.
Okay, let's talk about admission standards to a college or a school of vet medicine.
Back in 1916, you had to have a high school degree, and those admission standards increased until 1957 when you had to have 70 hours of college coursework.
Why did they continually increase?
Mainly because there was more and more knowledge in every subject.
You'd say, well, anatomy, they should have known, but anatomy has even increased.
But the...
Increase in knowledge was astounding in physiology and pharmacology, more in physiology, and toxicology, and microbiology.
Oh, microbiology is much improvement in finding the causes of diseases.
These students have a whole lot more to learn now than we used to because not too much was known.
And that means more hours.
and more help.
Do you think the students today that are admitted into the vet school are better than the ones that were admitted?
I mean, do you think they're better students, that they know more than the ones that were admitted back in the 1920s?
Well, they're screened, and they certainly should know more.
High schools are better.
And I hope they know a whole lot more.
I know some of us back in those days may not have gotten in under the present standards, but I think all that I know of and all of us were teaching and I knew were A's and B's.
I know I classify myself as an ordinary student.
I've had A's and B's and occasional C, but we didn't have
We didn't have that drive for those grade points.
We didn't have grade points back in there.
We had A, B, and C. And I think there was, in my time at least, it seems that our problem was to learn something and not bother with the grades.
I wasn't bothered about grades.
In fact, when I finished in 23, I had a bunch of extra hours.
I had things that I might want to use.
I took concrete construction on my own.
And I took herd book study and animal husbandry on my own.
And I took some Spanish on my own, mainly because I wanted to take some work
Mr. Ingenhuit, he later got his Ph.D. and went to Columbia.
Last I heard of him, he was teaching in Columbia University.
I think he left here and went to Columbia.
He was an outstanding teacher.
He came from Comfort, all those Germans out there, but he was excellent in Spanish.
And I took some engineering drawing from Mr. Geist.
who was quite an artist, and I took that on my own.
So now you think that the students are just much more grade-oriented, would you say?
They did become grade.
I don't know about right now.
I can't answer for that.
But I retired in 67.
But then when they increased admissions, yes, they were fighting for grade points.
Now another thing that happened on the admission standards I noticed according to your book is that in 1957 you needed 70 hours but then they started to decrease it.
You needed 68 hours in 1964 and then in 1975 you only needed 66 hours.
That occurred- Why did they do that?
I don't recall specifically but I know that was when price was deemed.
And they felt that they had perhaps too much on there and too much requirement.
And I know there's a change in attitude of what should be taken as pre-vet courses and, for example, the increase in math.
Some of us thought that
that math should be added.
Finally ended up with calculus.
And on graduate students, if I had a student who came in who looked superior and I felt would perhaps be headed for research, I always tried to get them to add math and also physical chemistry.
In my years,
I remember having taken a course at biophysical chemistry at Iowa State.
And I used more of that course than I think perhaps any course I had.
There were twelve of us in the class.
Ten of them were working on their PhDs.
One of them was working on a master's and I was trying to learn something.
And I really worked on that course.
And I didn't realize I learned as much until I got to using some when I got back.
And so I tried to, we had one of these superior East Pakistanis, Mia, who got his veterinary, he had a veterinary degree from Pakistan.
But he was an outstanding student.
He was an A student.
And I said, Mia, he picked me up as an advisor.
We didn't have advisors and counselors, but he'd come around for advice, and I took an interest in him.
And I said, get some mathematics.
He says, all right, and he made an A in calculus, and he'd come back, and I said,
Dr. Jensen talked to him about physical chemistry.
He said, oh, no.
She said, hopefully so.
I've heard too much about that.
Well, he had heard about that engineering course, and he was a bugger.
It was... Dr. Jensen was head of the department at that time, Fred Jensen.
And I knew him, and I thought that...
There was one course in there for other than chem engineers and then for majors in chemistry.
I think it was for engineers in general.
But it didn't go as deeply as the one that Mia was thinking about.
And I don't believe Mia took it, but he ended up
Going to California, the man from the physiology department at the University of California, I tried to get him here.
He wasn't head of the department, but he was teaching.
He came in my office one day, and I'd heard of him.
He's dean at Florida now.
And I said, you want to?
He was talking about how he liked Texas and everything, and how he liked the veterinary college.
I said, how much do you like it?
I said, I've got a job over there.
I'd like to have you.
But I knew something about him.
And he said, let me think about it.
But I had a nice letter from him when he got back.
They added five research projects put on him.
He got a promotion out of it.
And so they got a number of federal grants.
That is, I know it was a lump grant, but that is the time when California was getting a major part of these federal funds.
And they...
We're picking five students.
And he said, do you have one, two?
We have two to recommend physiology.
He said, I want to get one from each school.
And I said, he says, now, over in clinic there, I recommended a man.
He's in Washington now in research.
I said, now, what do you want, a cowboy or do you want a real student?
And he says, I said, I know the student.
I said, all right, but I said, this, and he's Pakistani.
But I said, he took, he followed my advice and has taken math, taken calculus, and I said, he's strong in math.
And...
He has a good chemistry background, and I said, he'll work for you.
He says, now, this is cattle.
And some of them over there knew that I was recommending him.
They said, he's afraid of cattle.
I said, he's not afraid of cattle.
I said, all those cowboys get over there, and they walk right into him, and he's a little hesitant.
But I said, you give him the responsibility, he'll do it.
So I recommended, he took me on my recommendation.
And I had a nice letter from Mia thanking me for the recommendation.
We went out there, and I got a letter from this man, and he said, that's the best graduate student we have.
And he says, now, how about this boy Smith?
And I said, yeah, Smith's all right.
Somebody else in the department.
He said, well, I'm going to take two from me and him.
He said, I wanted to get, he took one from Washington and took one from, I don't know, Michigan or Illinois or some other.
But he, they tried to spread it out.
But he said, I'm going to take two A&M.
But both of them did fine.
But he says, me at the top.
He says, at the top of the bunch.
And so I was quite happy about it.
And I later asked him, I said, was he harvested in this cattle?
He says, no.
He did, he was perfectly at home around those cattle.
And I said, well, some of them criticized me because they criticized, they didn't think Nier would make as good a man as this other one.
And that's why I asked you whether you wanted a cowboy or a student.
But he was an exception.
He and this other one, I was telling him about having five degrees, you know, got his matches.
But those were outstanding East Pakistanis.
Let's talk about the overall aim of the vet school.
Can you compare the overall aim of the vet school in the 1920s versus when you retired in the 1960s?
What is the vet school attempting to accomplish, and how did that change?
Well, in the 20s, of course, I was in teaching.
I was employed as a teacher.
and the research was done by the Dank-Schmitz force.
But looking back on it, I think that would have been better if we'd had some combination.
But I think that's been a marked improvement.
Another thing is the improved quality of the employees.
In fact, when I started this history, I had no idea of putting the degrees on that, but I was astounded at how many of them had PhDs and how the quality, how many of them.
Each department had PhDs in it, except, I think, clinic.
I don't think they had any.
But, in fact, now the entire department
the dean, the assistant dean, the two assistant deans, the dean of instruction, and that is Wally Bay, and the dean of research, associate deans, they're associate deans.
They're all PhDs in the dean's office.
And at one time, there were none.
When Price had it, there were none in there.
Except when Meyer came in, Meyer was a PhD.
as the Associate Dean of Research.
I don't recall the exact year he retired.
So do you see that as an improvement?
Yes, I do.
I think the quality... And these men are through with their schoolwork, and most of them are interested in research.
And that's improved a great deal.
So the aim has shifted away then toward research and away from just training practitioners then?
Would you say that?
No, I think that our product is primarily a practitioner.
Still today?
Yes, I think so.
Yes, absolutely.
In fact, most of them are doing small animal practice.
I'd like to see more of them in large animal practice.
But a lot of them go into general practice to take care of all.
See, in small communities, they're forced into it, and some of them by choice.
That's why some of them go to small communities.
But if they want to go in for the money, so to speak, I'd like to think they're in the minority.
But if they go into a city, why, they are small animal practitioners.
like Houston and Dallas.
But some of them, the edges of the cities are large animal practice.
Some of them in the cities go out and dairy practice.
